ju Kapur's Difficult Daughters and the Cause of Female Literacy in India / rCarbone, Paola -- tThe Trial of Jomo Kenyatta, by Montagu Slater: Oral Tradition and Fundamental Rights in the Trial / rLanzoni, Lisa -- t'n Droë Wit Seisoen in die Stormkaap: André Brink and the Fundamental Rights of the Afrikaners in Apartheid South Africa / rNicolini, Matteo -- tThe Definition of "Linguistic Minority" / rTomaselli, Alessandra / Panzeri, Lino -- tRights of Humans/Rights of Nature: The Language of Environmental Rights in UN Documents / rAdami, Valentina -- tOn Crimes, Punishments, and Words: Legal and Language Issues in Cesare Beccaria's Works / rLogaldo, Mara -- tDignity and Disgrace in Law and Literature / rGaakeer, Jeanne -- tContributors -- tIndex  aThe idea of human rights is not new. But the importance of taking rights seriously has never been more urgent. The eighteen essays which comprise Literature and Human Rights are written as a contribution to this vital debate. Each moreover is written in the spirit of interdisciplinarity, reaching across the myriad constitutive disciplines of law, literature and the humanities in order to present an array of alternative perspectives on the nature and meaning of human rights in the modern world. The taking of human rights seriously, it will be suggested, depends just as much on taking seriously the idea of the human as it does the idea of rights.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aHuman rights in literature. 0aHuman rightsxLanguage. 0aLaw and literature. 0aLiterature and society. 0aSocial justice in literature. 4aLiterature. 4ahuman rights. 4alanguage. 4alaw. 70(DE-601)1057064180(DE-588)4129916-4aSprachanalyse2gnd 70(DE-601)1060885560(DE-588)4074725-6aMenschenrecht2gnd 70(DE-601)1061547450(DE-588)4056449-6aSprache2gnd 70(DE-601)1062